
This project gives an easy way to switch between development projects
and setup your environment as needed for each one.

General:

The 'g' command will take to you any development sandbox directory
inside 'SANDBOXES_ROOT' (with tab completion). It will set 'SANDBOX'
to the name of the sandbox (directory name), and SANDBOX_DIR to the
root of the sandbox.

'.sandbox' is sourced when entering a sandbox. put whatever custom
commands .you need here (export GOPATH, entering virtualenv or a
chroot, etc). If you export 'SANDBOX_DEFAULT' you will jump directly
to that directory instead of the root.

The 'g' command with no arguments will take you to the SANDBOX_DEFAULT
directory of the current sandbox.

Sublime:

The script "sublime" will invoke sublime_text with a per-sandbox
project file (which is autocreated if necessary).

SANDBOX and SANDBOX_DIR are used by the "sublime" wrapper to create or
use a per-sandbox project file.

Emacs:

emacs.README shows how to have the emacs 'desktop' feature also adjust
to your current sandbox.

Command Prompt:

You can set your prompt to include the current sandbox with:

function _sandbox {
  [ -n "$SANDBOX" ] && echo "($SANDBOX)" || echo "$USER"
}
export PS1="\[\e]0;\u@\h: \w\a\]\$(_sandbox)\$"

export PS1="\[\e]0;\u@\h: \w\a\]\${SANDBOX:-$USER}\$"

Atom:
  function a() {
    if [[ "${SANDBOX_DEFAULT}" != "${SANDBOX_DIR}" ]]; then
      atom -n "${SANDBOX_DEFAULT}" "${SANDBOX_DIR}"
    else
      atom -n "${SANDBOX_DIR}"
    fi
  }

Setup:

Set any of the config variables you want to change from default, then
source 'bashrc' from your .bashrc file.

  . "${HOME}/sand/sandbox/bashrc"


Config ENVS:
  SANDBOXES_ROOT: root directory for sandboxes. Default ~/sand

  SUBLIME: Name of sublime executable (usually /custom/path/sublime_text).
           Default 'sublime_text'.

  SUBLIME_LIB_DIR: Directory in which to store project files for sandboxes.
                   Default ~/lib/sublime
